# Kung Fu Chess — Cursor Agent Instructions

**Read this file first.** It is the canonical entry point for Cursor Agent in this repo.

## Cursor workflow

1. Identify which architectural layer the task belongs to (see Architecture below)
2. Apply layer-specific rules from `.cursor/rules/` when editing matching paths
3. Keep diffs minimal — change only what the task requires
4. After adding `.cpp` files, update `build.bat` and `CMakeLists.txt`
5. Verify with `.\build.bat` or `.\build.bat test` when logic changes
6. If the change affects layout, architecture, layers, build, input protocol, or conventions — update the instruction files to match:
   - `.cursor/rules/agents.mdc` (primary)
   - `AGENTS.md` (keep in sync with agents.mdc)
   - Relevant `.cursor/rules/*.mdc` (e.g. `architecture.mdc`, `model-rules.mdc`)
7. Do not commit unless the user explicitly asks

### Layer rule files (apply when editing matching files)

| Rule file | Globs |
|-----------|-------|
| `cpp-files.mdc` | `src/**`, `include/**` |
| `model-rules.mdc` | `model/`, `rules/` |
| `engine-realtime.mdc` | `engine/`, `realtime/` |
| `io-input-view.mdc` | `io/`, `input/`, `view/`, `texttests/`, `main.cpp`, `App` |

## Stack

- C++17, STL only, no third-party deps
- Headers in `include/`, sources in `src/`
- Build: `.\build.bat` builds and runs the app (`src\main.cpp` composition root); `.\build.bat test` builds and runs the engine test suite

## Language

- **All comments must be in English** — never Hebrew or mixed-language comments
- Identifiers, error strings, and reason codes: English only

## Layout

```
include/
├── model/       Board, Piece, Position, GameState
├── rules/       IPieceRule strategies, RuleEngine
├── realtime/    Motion, RealTimeArbiter
├── engine/      GameEngine
├── io/          BoardParser, BoardPrinter
├── input/       Controller, BoardMapper
├── view/        Renderer, ImageView
├── texttests/   ScriptParser, ScriptRunner
└── App.h        Composition root
```

> Legacy `Board.h`/`Board.cpp`, `Game.h`/`Game.cpp`, `MoveRules.h`/`MoveRules.cpp` are removed.
> `src/main.cpp` is the composition root: it delegates entirely to
> `ScriptRunner::run(std::cin, std::cout)`, which parses the `Board:`/`Commands:` protocol via
> `ScriptParser`/`BoardParser` and replays it against `GameEngine` + `Controller` + `BoardPrinter`.

## Architecture

Dependencies point inward only:

```
main/App → input/view/io → engine → rules/realtime → model
```

| Layer | Key types | Responsibility |
|-------|-----------|----------------|
| Model | `Board`, `Piece`, `Position`, `GameState` | Grid data, bounds — no I/O or rules |
| Rules | `IPieceRule`, `RuleEngine` | Move legality via Strategy pattern |
| Realtime | `Motion`, `RealTimeArbiter` | Timed movement, capture on arrival |
| Engine | `GameEngine` | Orchestrates model + rules + realtime |
| I/O | `BoardParser`, `BoardPrinter` | Parse/serialize board text |
| Input | `Controller`, `BoardMapper` | Map clicks/pixels to engine calls |
| View | `Renderer`, `ImageView` | Render `GameSnapshot` only |
| App | `App`, `main` | Wire layers; dispatch commands |

### Patterns

- **Strategy**: `IPieceRule` per piece; `ruleFor(kind)` factory
- **DTO**: `MoveResult`, `MoveValidation`, `GameSnapshot`, `ArrivalEvent`
- **Facade**: `GameEngine` is the single game-logic entry point
- **Snapshot**: view never mutates `Board` directly

## Input format (do not change without explicit request)

1. Board rows until `Board:` marker (tokens: `.`, `wK`, `bQ`)
2. `Commands:` — `click X Y`, `jump X Y`, `wait MS`, `print board`
3. Errors to stdout: `ERROR UNKNOWN_TOKEN`, `ERROR ROW_WIDTH_MISMATCH`
4. `jump X Y` lifts the piece at that cell airborne in place for a fixed 1s duration (bypasses normal
   travel time since it never changes squares); it lands back down and captures whatever occupies the
   square by then. Rejected if the cell is empty or that color already has a motion in flight.

## Code style

- Include guards: `#ifndef BOARD_H` / `#define BOARD_H` / `#endif`
- Classes: PascalCase; methods: camelCase
- Prefer `const` methods and references for read-only params
- File-local helpers as `static` in `.cpp` files
- **Header vs implementation (strict):** `.h` files are headers only — declarations, include guards, `static constexpr` constants, defaulted members. All function/method bodies go in the matching `.cpp`; never define function bodies inline in a header.
